Purpose of the respiratory system

  1. Provide oxygen to our cells at a rate that is adequate for their needs
  2. Eliminate waste gases such as carbon dioxide
  3. Talk and smell
  4. Humidifies and warms the air to match your body –cold and dry air is not nice to breathe in
  5. Protects your airways from harmful substances and irritants i.e. cough reflex, mucous secretions etc.

Neural control of breathing

Pons

Medulla

Respiratory centres

Initiates inspiration

Diaphragm motor neurons

C3, 4, 5 –phrenic nerve

External intercostal motor neurons

T1 –T12

DRG

4 groups of neurons:

  1. Drivers of expiratory activity –Bötzingercomplex
  2. Motor neurons that control the pharynx and larynx –nucleus ambiguus
  3. Premotor neurons that project down to the spinal cord (both inspand exp).
  4. Respiratory rhythm generator -PreBötzingercomplex

Expiration

VRG

Pons (PRG)

2 regions

Pneumotaxiccentre

  • Terminates inspiration.
  • Depth and rate of breathing.
  • Smooth transition from inspiration to expiration and vice versa.

Apneustic centre

  • Delays the inspiratory ‘off’ switch

Results in prolonged and deep inspiratory pattern
